				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Their English grammar sucks, but they laugh at our attempts to deter them.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Probably everyone by now met the following text while surfing the internet: &quot;Enter the number you see in the box&quot; and, following it, a terribly distorted image. That's a pictocode (ticket, captcha, human verification code).
<br />
In the process of it's work, the X****r program, can succesfully recognize tickets, automatically downloading the picture and decoding it. As practice showed us, it takes 1-1,5 seconds to decode such a ticket, and usually even less than that (on a PC with a CPU 1 Ghz). Such a picture's size is usually not more than 3-5Kb so it's downloading time is less than a second.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
<img src="http://www.commutercars.com/bryan/images/2006/XRumer.jpg" border="0" />
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">These are by far not all the types of tickets, the more trivial ones are not shown, they were used in the early versions of forums, but still appea–∫ in some of them.
<br />
X****r automatically recognizes which type of tickets is used and chooses the proper decoding algorythm. All this can be clearly seen in the demo version of the software which you can download on our site, after registration. 
<br />

<br />
You may think that making such a powerful decoder is meaningless - a great lot of forums do not use pictocode. It is not.
<br />
It is the more popular forums, with a higher number of users and visitors, make use of the more powerful protection from robots - among others they use the pictocode. Posting your mesages on these forums gives the best returns!</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Yes, this is right off their copyrighted web site (with the obvious exception of the censoring since I don't want to advertise for them). I don't really care, though . . . </span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">In no way X****r acts like a spam-bot since spam is defined in legislation as 'unsolicited email', whereas X****r simply posts messages created by users, which cannot be illegal providing the user does not violate the legislation . . .</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
